Acquire

Getting the data from ‘Global Food Prices’ database. Since, it contains more than 7 lakh records, filtering the food price data only for India, which comes close to 68K records.

Transform, Explore and Model

To plot a line graph of price trend of all commodities over time.

library(ggplot2)
library(dplyr)
## 
## Attaching package: 'dplyr'
## The following objects are masked from 'package:stats':
## 
##     filter, lag
## The following objects are masked from 'package:base':
## 
##     intersect, setdiff, setequal, union
ggplot(df, aes(x=df$Year, y=df$Price)) + geom_line(aes(color=df$Commodity)) + xlab("Year") + ylab("Price") + scale_color_discrete(name="Commodity")

Conclusion: This clearly shows that, there is a general increase in price trend of all commodities, but it is not clearly distinguishable in this type of graph. Also, there is a large variance in a price of a particular commodity in a particular year.

To make it more clear, we are plotting a point graph.

library(scales)
df1 <- subset(df, df$Commodity %in% c("Mustard_oil", "Onions", "Potatoes", "Rice", "Salt", "Sugar", "Wheat"))
ggplot(df1, aes(x = df1$Commodity, y = df1$Price)) + theme(legend.position="top", axis.text=element_text(size = 6)) + geom_point(aes(color=df1$Year), alpha = 0.5, size = 1.5, position = position_jitter(width = 0.25, height = 0)) + scale_x_discrete(name="Commodity") + scale_color_continuous(name="", breaks=c(1995,2000,2005,2010,2015), labels=c("'95", "'00", "'05", "'10", "'15")) + scale_color_gradient2(name="",breaks=c(1995,2000,2005,2010,2015), labels=c("'95", "'00", "'05", "'10", "'15"), low = muted("blue"), high = muted("red"), mid="gray60", midpoint = 2005 ) + ylab("Price")
## Scale for 'colour' is already present. Adding another scale for
## 'colour', which will replace the existing scale.

Conclusion: This clearly shows that, Mustard oil has the highest price among these 7 commodities. Also there is a clear indication of increase in price of the commodities over time. There is some indication that, prices of onions and potatoes has some what reduced as the darker and denser areas are not at the top.

Commodity price relative to max in period

Overall price trend of all commodities over time. Since different commodities will clearly have different prices, we are making them comparable by scaling based on their maximum price within our time-frame.

overallPriceTrend <- df %>% group_by(Commodity, Year) %>% summarise(globalAveragePrice = mean(Price) / max(Price))
str(overallPriceTrend)
## Classes 'grouped_df', 'tbl_df', 'tbl' and 'data.frame':  173 obs. of  3 variables:
##  $ Commodity         : chr  "Ghee" "Ghee" "Ghee" "Groundnut_oil" ...
##  $ Year              : int  2015 2016 2017 2012 2013 2014 2015 2016 2017 2015 ...
##  $ globalAveragePrice: num  0.624 0.634 0.677 0.741 0.692 ...
##  - attr(*, "vars")= chr "Commodity"
##  - attr(*, "drop")= logi TRUE
# we are selecing a smaller sample for plotting commodities
commodities <- c("Mustard_oil", "Potatoes", "Rice", "Salt", "Sugar", "Wheat", "Onions")
priceTrend <- df %>% select(Price, Commodity, Year) %>% filter(Commodity %in% commodities) %>% group_by(Commodity, Year) %>% summarise(globalAveragePrice = mean(Price) / max(Price))
str(priceTrend)
## Classes 'grouped_df', 'tbl_df', 'tbl' and 'data.frame':  106 obs. of  3 variables:
##  $ Commodity         : chr  "Mustard_oil" "Mustard_oil" "Mustard_oil" "Mustard_oil" ...

##  - attr(*, "vars")= chr "Commodity"
##  - attr(*, "drop")= logi TRUE
# we will now plot a graph
library(forcats)
colournames <- c("Mustard_oil" = "#383838", "Potatoes" = "#fea814", "Rice" = "#7fff00", "Salt" = "#cccccc", "Sugar" = "#4fcfff", "Wheat" = "#005692", "Onions" = "#00ffff")
# Specify commodity levels for use in our legend
fctLevels <- c("Rice", "Sugar", "Wheat", "Mustard_oil", "Onions", "Potatoes", "Salt")
ggplot(priceTrend, aes(x = Year, y = globalAveragePrice)) +
  geom_smooth(aes(colour = fct_relevel(Commodity, fctLevels)), se = FALSE, size = 1.8, linetype = 5) +
  geom_smooth(data = overallPriceTrend, colour = "red", se = FALSE, size = 3.5) +
  geom_line(aes(size = "All Commodities", linetype = NA), colour = "red") +
  scale_colour_manual(values = colournames) +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(1994, 2017, 2)) +
  scale_y_continuous(limits = c(0.2, 0.8), labels = c("Min", "Max"), breaks = c(0.2, 0.8)) +
  labs(title = "Average Indian Commodity Prices over Time",
       subtitle = "Commodity Price Relative to Max in Period",
       caption = "Data from https://data.humdata.org/dataset/wfp-food-prices",
       x = "", 
       y = "",
       colour = "Commodity",
       size = "") +
  theme_classic()

Insight

From the graph, we see that there is a gradual decrease in overall prices, but it is somewhat negated in the last 4 years. The Onion prices has increased over time. The potato prices has decreased over time. There is a gradual increase in mustard oil prices followed by a decrease. The prices of sugar and wheat have mostly a flattened trend having almost the same price in 2016 when compared to 1994. The price of rice has decreased followed by an increase in the last 4 years.

dfmustard <- dfpredict %>% filter(Commodity==c("Mustard_oil")) %>% select(Date, Price)

colnames(dfmustard1) <- c('ds', 'y')
library(prophet)
## Loading required package: Rcpp
m <- prophet(dfmustard1)
## Warning in set_auto_seasonalities(m): Disabling weekly seasonality. Run
## prophet with `weekly.seasonality=TRUE` to override this.
## Initial log joint probability = -3.04765
## Optimization terminated normally: 
##   Convergence detected: relative gradient magnitude is below tolerance
future <- make_future_dataframe(m, period=12, freq="m")
forecast <- predict(m, future)
plot(m, forecast)

Conclusion: This clearly shows that, the price of Mustard oil is increasing in the next 12 months. But the variablility of the price for a particular date is more across all the markets of India.
